      "description": "By Periphery III, Matt Halpern's Meinl Byzance cymbal setup was the fully realized system that had begun its evolution with Periphery II. The Byzance series — Meinl's handcrafted B20 bronze line, made in Turkey using traditional casting and hammering methods — provided the dark, complex, layered cymbal voice that had become as fundamental to the Periphery sound as Misha Mansoor's seven-string guitar tone.\n\nThe Byzance Extra Dry crashes were central to Select Difficulty's aggressive tracks. Extra Dry cymbals feature a lathed, unfinished surface that creates a fast-decaying, slightly trashier crash character — perfect for tracks like \"The Price Is Wrong\" and \"Motormouth\" where crashes hit frequently and need to decay quickly to avoid building up into a wash that obscures the rhythmic details that djent's syncopated arrangements require.\n\nThe 14\" Byzance Dual hi-hats provided Halpern with the articulation platform for Select Difficulty's intricate hi-hat work. Dual cymbals combine two different surface treatments into one instrument, creating a more complex, layered chick sound that rewards close listening. On \"Lune\" — the album's most textured, dynamic track — Halpern's hi-hat work is a study in what articulate, complex cymbals allow: each note distinct, each velocity level audible, each open-close-open figure a rhythmic event rather than mere timekeeping.\n\nThe 22\" Byzance Extra Dry Medium Ride anchored the setup's right side, providing a clear ping for riding passages without the wash buildup that lighter rides produce under Periphery's sustained playing intensities. The Extra Dry surface gave the ride a slightly raw, responsive quality — closer to the feel of unlathed traditional cymbals than the polished brightness of mainstream metal rides.\n\nFor the Grammy-nominated performance on \"The Price Is Wrong,\" the Byzance setup contributed the cymbal vocabulary that made the track's aggressiveness feel musical rather than merely loud: the crashes accent rather than dominate, the ride defines without overwhelming, and the china adds punctuation without clutter.",
